# Solving the `eq_zero_of_I_zero_equinum` lemma in Lean 4

We need to prove that if `I 0 ∼ I n`, then `n = 0`. Here, `I k` denotes the set `{x : ℕ | x < k}`. So `I 0` is the empty set `{x : ℕ | x < 0}`, which is indeed empty. `I n` is the set `{x : ℕ | x < n}`.

The statement `↑(I 0) ∼ ↑(I n)` means that the image of `I 0` under the coercion `↑` is equivalent to the image of `I n` under the coercion `↑`. Since `I 0` is empty, its image is also empty. So we have `∅ ∼ ↑(I n)`. This means `↑(I n)` must be empty. `↑(I n)` is the set `{x : ℕ | x < n}` coerced to `Set ℕ`. This set is empty if and only if `n = 0`. So if `↑(I n)` is empty, then `n = 0`.

